\sphinxAtStartPar
This package contains utilities to interact with the AI Squared technology stack, particularly with developing and deploying models to the AI Squared Platform or other applications developed through the AI Squared JavaScript SDK.

\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Current Production Version:} \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{0.3.3}}

\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{View this Documentation in PDF Format}}.

\chapter{Installation}
\label{\detokenize{index:installation}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
This package is available through \sphinxhref{https://pypi.org}{Pypi} and can be installed by running the following command:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
pip\PYG{+w}{ }install\PYG{+w}{ }aisquared
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
Alternatively, the latest version of the software can be installed directly from GitHub using the following command:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
pip\PYG{+w}{ }install\PYG{+w}{ }git+https://github.com/AISquaredInc/aisquared
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\subparagraph{aisquared.config.preprocessing package}
\label{\detokenize{aisquared.config.preprocessing:aisquared-config-preprocessing-package}}\label{\detokenize{aisquared.config.preprocessing::doc}}

\subparagraph{Module contents}
\label{\detokenize{aisquared.config.preprocessing:module-aisquared.config.preprocessing}}\label{\detokenize{aisquared.config.preprocessing:module-contents}}\index{module@\spxentry{module}!aisquared.config.preprocessing@\spxentry{aisquared.config.preprocessing}}\index{aisquared.config.preprocessing@\spxentry{aisquared.config.preprocessing}!module@\spxentry{module}}\begin{description}
\sphinxlineitem{The aisquared.config.preprocessing subpackage contains utilities to configure the preprocessing of data in the data pipeline.  It contains}
\sphinxAtStartPar
three separate subpackages, aisquared.config.preprocessing.text, aisquared.config.preprocessing.image, and aisquared.config.preprocessing.tabular, which configure the preprocessing of different types of data.

\end{description}

\paragraph{aisquared.logging package}

\paragraph{aisquared.platform package}
\label{\detokenize{aisquared.platform:aisquared-platform-package}}\label{\detokenize{aisquared.platform::doc}}

\subparagraph{Module contents}
\label{\detokenize{aisquared.platform:module-aisquared.platform}}\label{\detokenize{aisquared.platform:module-contents}}\index{module@\spxentry{module}!aisquared.platform@\spxentry{aisquared.platform}}\index{aisquared.platform@\spxentry{aisquared.platform}!module@\spxentry{module}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Utilities for interacting with the AI Squared Platform.

\sphinxAtStartPar
The primary class within this subpackage is the \sphinxtitleref{AISquaredPlatformClient} class, which has the
capabilities to interact with much of the functionality in the AI Squared platform. For more
information about this class, please see its documentation.

\paragraph{aisquared.serving package}
\label{\detokenize{aisquared.serving:aisquared-serving-package}}\label{\detokenize{aisquared.serving::doc}}

\subparagraph{Module contents}
\label{\detokenize{aisquared.serving:module-aisquared.serving}}\label{\detokenize{aisquared.serving:module-contents}}\index{module@\spxentry{module}!aisquared.serving@\spxentry{aisquared.serving}}\index{aisquared.serving@\spxentry{aisquared.serving}!module@\spxentry{module}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
The aisquared.serving package contains utilities to serve models to a local REST endpoint.

\sphinxAtStartPar
Here is an example of how to serve a simple keras model using these utilities:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{g+gp}{\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{} }\PYG{c+c1}{\PYGZsh{} Assume model is already trained and stored in memory as model}
\PYG{g+gp}{\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{} }\PYG{k+kn}{from} \PYG{n+nn}{aisquared} \PYG{k+kn}{import} \PYG{n}{serving}
\PYG{g+gp}{\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{} }\PYG{n}{serving}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{save\PYGZus{}keras\PYGZus{}model}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{model}\PYG{p}{,} \PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{l+s+s1}{my\PYGZus{}model}\PYG{l+s+s1}{\PYGZsq{}}\PYG{p}{)}
\PYG{g+gp}{\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{} }\PYG{n}{serving}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{deploy\PYGZus{}model}\PYG{p}{(}
\PYG{g+go}{    \PYGZsq{}my\PYGZus{}model\PYGZsq{},}
\PYG{g+go}{    \PYGZsq{}keras\PYGZsq{},}
\PYG{g+go}{    additional\PYGZus{}functions\PYGZus{}file = \PYGZsq{}\PYGZlt{}optional file containing `preprocess` and `postprocess` functions, if applicable\PYGZgt{}\PYGZsq{}}
\PYG{g+go}{)}
\PYG{g+go}{App created successfullly. Serving and awaiting requests}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
And to retrieve predictions from the model:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{g+gp}{\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{} }\PYG{c+c1}{\PYGZsh{} From a separate terminal, assume data is already loaded}
\PYG{g+gp}{\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{} }\PYG{k+kn}{from} \PYG{n+nn}{aisquared} \PYG{k+kn}{import} \PYG{n}{serving}
\PYG{g+gp}{\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{}\PYGZgt{} }\PYG{n}{serving}\PYG{o}{.}\PYG{n}{get\PYGZus{}remote\PYGZus{}predictions}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{data}\PYG{p}{)} \PYG{c+c1}{\PYGZsh{} Do not need to change host or port if predicting from the same machine}
\PYG{g+go}{*predictions*}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
Additional utilities to use with the \sphinxtitleref{aisquared} package. These utilities currently consist of two functions, the
\sphinxtitleref{mimic\_model} and \sphinxtitleref{get\_model} functions. They utilize functionality that exists in our open source package BeyondML
to train teacher\sphinxhyphen{}student models

\sphinxAtStartPar
To see in\sphinxhyphen{}depth examples of how to use these functions, please visit our GitHub repository at \sphinxurl{https://github.com/AISquaredInc/MimicModelExamples}


\subparagraph{Submodules}
\label{\detokenize{aisquared.utils:submodules}}
